  "text": "While the long C-terminal helix of Rrp14 bridges domains II and VI, the Ssf1-Rrp15 complex is positioned at the interface of domains I and VI (Fig. 2a) . Here, Ssf1 occupies the same position as Rpl31, which in the later Nog2-containing pre-60S particles binds at the interface of domains III and VI near the polypeptide exit tunnel (PET) [CITATION_1] . The PET, which is created by domains I, III and VI at the solvent-exposed side, is already formed in the Nog2 particle, where it is blocked by the C-terminal domain (CTD) of the GTPase Nog1 (Fig. 2c, d ).",
